The ^*BCap Gemini Ernst & Young World Top Invitational Pairs^*N is often referred to as "The Wimbledon of Bridge". This event is held every January at the beautiful ^*BHotel Des Indes^*N in The Hague, The Netherlands. The organizers of the Cap Gemini invite 16 world class partnerships to compete in this event each year and the field is always very strong.

Full coverage of the 2001 Cap Gemini, including ^*BOnline Vugraph^*N of every deal at all 8 tables, is available through:

|cs|3|at|^-{ ^*Hwww.bridgeplaza.com^*N }
^-
You can click on the green rectangle above to be taken to this web site in a new browser window.

This year's Cap Gemini was the 15th running of this event. For the first time in history the defending champions, ^*BZia Mahmood^*N and ^*BAndrew Robson^*N, were able to retain the title. The fact that Zia and Andrew are not a regular partnership makes this accomplishment all the more impressive.

Zia and Andrew share several characteristics that we admire very much. They are both natural bidders and great card players and they have both contributed a great deal toward helping to publicize bridge. You have to be a highly competitive person to succeed in the international bridge circuit, but Zia and Andrew are still able to be courteous and fun with both their partners and their opponents.


